    },
    {
      quote: "The tentative output lives in the claim cells, NOT in the original cell's state.",
      interpretation-A: "The original cell has NO output at all during evaluation — its yield fields are unbound. Only claim cells hold values. If claims pass, the yields are filled from claim cell data.",
      interpretation-B: "The original cell's yield fields hold a tentative value that is NOT YET FROZEN. Claim cells reference this tentative value. If claims pass, the tentative value is promoted to frozen.",
      concrete-bug: "Under A, there's no tentative value to check — claim cells must generate their own expected values from the ∴ block. Under B, the cell has a tentative output that claim cells compare against. An implementor choosing A would build claim cells that re-derive expected outputs; choosing B would build claim cells that validate existing outputs. Completely different architectures."
    },
